    <!-- Benefits -->
    <section id="benefits" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 class="title-lg">Potential benefits</h2>
        <p class="lead">What research and clinical experience suggest chiropractic care may help with during pregnancy</p>
        <div class="grid grid-3 benefits">
          <div class="card"><div class="p">
            <h3 class="title-md">Back & pelvic pain relief</h3>
            <p class="muted">Targeted manual therapy and exercise can reduce pregnancy‑related low back and pelvic girdle pain in many people. Responses vary; combining care with activity and sleep strategies often works best.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p">
            <h3 class="title-md">Gentle, non‑drug options</h3>
            <p class="muted">For those minimizing medications, chiropractic provides non‑pharmacologic options such as mobilization, soft tissue work, and tailored exercises.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p">
            <h3 class="title-md">Improved mobility & function</h3>
            <p class="muted">Restoring comfortable movement patterns may make daily tasks—standing, walking, lifting, and sleeping—easier through the trimesters.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p">
            <h3 class="title-md">Comfort‑focused care</h3>
            <p class="muted">Side‑lying, pregnancy pillows, and low‑force techniques help accommodate body changes while prioritizing comfort.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p">
            <h3 class="title-md">Education & self‑management</h3>
            <p class="muted">Expect guidance on posture, sleep positions, pelvic support belts, and safe strength/mobility routines you can continue at home.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p">
            <h3 class="title-md">Collaborative support</h3>
            <p class="muted">Chiropractors can coordinate with OB/midwives and physical therapists to align care with your pregnancy plan and any medical considerations.</p>
          </div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Safety -->
    <section id="safety" class="section">
      <div class="container grid grid-2">
        <div class="card"><div class="p">
          <h2 class="title-lg">Safety first</h2>
          <p class="lead">When used appropriately, chiropractic care is generally considered safe in pregnancy. Screening helps tailor care to you.</p>
          <h3 class="title-md" style="margin-top:8px">Common safety adaptations</h3>
          <ul class="muted list">
            <li>Side‑lying or elevated positions instead of prolonged flat‑on‑back, especially after mid‑pregnancy.</li>
            <li>Avoiding direct abdominal pressure; using pregnancy pillows and cut‑out tables.</li>
            <li>Favoring gentle mobilization or instrument‑assisted adjustments when appropriate.</li>
            <li>Short, comfortable session lengths with frequent check‑ins.</li>
          </ul>
        </div></div>
        <div class="card"><div class="p">
          <h3 class="title-md">Red flags — seek medical care first</h3>
          <p class="muted">Consult your obstetric provider before chiropractic care if you have:</p>
          <ul class="muted list">
            <li>Vaginal bleeding, fluid leakage, or preterm labor concerns</li>
            <li>Placenta previa or placental abruption</li>
            <li>Severe preeclampsia, uncontrolled hypertension, or significant swelling/headache/vision changes</li>
            <li>Severe or progressive neurologic deficits</li>
            <li>Fever, infection, or sudden severe abdominal pain</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="muted" style="font-size:12px">This is not a complete list. When in doubt, check with your OB or midwife.</p>
        </div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What to expect -->
    <section id="what-to-expect" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 class="title-lg">What to expect at a visit</h2>
        <div class="grid grid-3">
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">1) A thoughtful intake</h3><p class="muted">History, goals, daily demands, sleep, and activity are reviewed alongside pregnancy timeline and medical considerations.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">2) Screening & exam</h3><p class="muted">Gentle movement tests for the spine, pelvis, and ribs; neurological screening when needed; shared decision‑making on care plan.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">3) Gentle hands‑on care</h3><p class="muted">Options include mobilization, soft‑tissue techniques, and, when suitable, low‑force or traditional adjustments adapted for pregnancy.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">4) Exercise & supports</h3><p class="muted">Simple, safe home exercises for hips, glutes, core and breathing; advice on pelvic belts, pillows, and activity pacing.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">5) Education</h3><p class="muted">Ergonomics, sleep positions (e.g., side‑lying with pillow support), and movement strategies for daily comfort.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">6) Follow‑up plan</h3><p class="muted">Frequency is individualized based on goals, response to care, and guidance from your obstetric provider.</p></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Techniques -->
    <section id="techniques" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 class="title-lg">Common techniques & tools</h2>
        <p class="lead">Your chiropractor will choose options based on comfort, stage of pregnancy, and goals.</p>
        <div class="grid grid-3">
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">Mobilization</h3><p class="muted">Gentle, graded movements to restore joint motion without quick thrusts.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">HVLA adjustments (adapted)</h3><p class="muted">When appropriate and consented, quick, precise thrusts may be used with positioning and force adapted for pregnancy.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">Instrument‑assisted</h3><p class="muted">Low‑force impulses to specific joints or soft tissues; often well‑tolerated. (e.g., Activator®, ArthroStim®)</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">Soft‑tissue therapy</h3><p class="muted">Myofascial release, trigger point work, and gentle rib cage techniques to ease tension.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">Exercise & breathing</h3><p class="muted">Hip/glute strength, pelvic control, spinal mobility, and diaphragmatic breathing to support posture and comfort.</p></div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="p"><h3 class="title-md">Ergonomics & supports</h3><p class="muted">Pillows, pelvic belts, taping, and activity modification strategies for day‑to‑day relief.</p></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Evidence -->
    <section id="evidence" class="section">
      <div class="container grid grid-2">
        <div class="card"><div class="p">
          <h2 class="title-lg">What does the evidence say?</h2>
          <h3 class="title-md" style="margin-top:8px">Current picture</h3>
          <ul class="muted list">
            <li>Pregnancy‑related low back and pelvic girdle pain are common. Non‑drug care such as manual therapy and exercise are often recommended first‑line.</li>
            <li>Research on chiropractic/manual therapy shows <em>promising but mixed</em> results for pain and function. Study quality varies; more high‑quality trials are needed.</li>
            <li>Safety data are limited but generally reassuring when contraindications are screened and care is adapted to pregnancy.</li>
            <li>Best outcomes tend to come from <strong>multimodal care</strong>: education, activity changes, exercise, and appropriately selected manual therapy.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="muted" style="font-size:12px">Need a version with peer‑reviewed citations? I can add them for you.</p>
        </div></div>
        <div class="card"><div class="p" id="talk">
          <h3 class="title-md">Shared decision‑making</h3>
          <p class="muted">Talk with your OB/midwife and chiropractor about goals, preferences, and medical considerations. Reassess regularly and choose the gentlest effective option.</p>
          <a class="btn" href="#resources" style="margin-top:10px; display:inline-block">Discussion checklist (download soon)</a>
        </div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section id="faq" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 class="title-lg">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <details>
          <summary>Is chiropractic safe during pregnancy?</summary>
          <div class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">When contraindications are screened and techniques are adapted, serious adverse events appear rare. Always coordinate with your obstetric provider and inform your chiropractor of any new symptoms.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Do I need a referral?</summary>
          <div class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">In many places you can self‑refer, but check your local regulations and insurance. Coordinated care with OB/midwife is encouraged.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How many visits will I need?</summary>
          <div class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">It depends on your goals, symptom severity, and response to care. Many people notice changes within a few visits; others benefit from periodic check‑ins along with home exercise.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Can chiropractic help with labor or birth outcomes?</summary>
          <div class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">Evidence is limited. Chiropractic care is best framed around comfort, mobility, and function during pregnancy rather than specific birth outcomes.</div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Resources -->
    <section id="resources" class="section">
      <div class="container grid grid-2">
        <div class="card"><div class="p">
          <h2 class="title-lg">Resources & next steps</h2>
          <h3 class="title-md">Conversation starters</h3>
          <ul class="muted list">
            <li>My goals are… (e.g., sleep better, walk comfortably, reduce pelvic pain)</li>
            <li>Any medical considerations I should share? (e.g., placenta previa, hypertension, prior injuries)</li>
            <li>Which gentle techniques fit my preferences?</li>
            <li>What home exercises and supports should I start this week?</li>
          </ul>
        </div></div>
        <div class="card"><div class="p">
          <h3 class="title-md">Disclaimer</h3>
          <p class="muted">This site provides educational information only and does not replace medical advice. Always consult your obstetric provider about new or worsening symptoms and before starting any new treatment.</p>
        </div></div>
